<waf_detector_guide>
<title>WAF DETECTION AND FINGERPRINTING</title>

<critical>Web Application Firewalls (WAFs) are the first line of defense encountered during penetration testing. Accurate WAF identification is essential for selecting appropriate bypass techniques and avoiding detection. Different WAF vendors have distinct signatures, blocking behaviors, and weaknesses. Fingerprinting the WAF enables targeted evasion strategies.</critical>

<scope>
- WAF presence detection through behavioral analysis
- Vendor-specific fingerprinting (Cloudflare, Akamai, AWS WAF, etc.)
- Blocking behavior analysis and threshold identification
- Rate limiting discovery and characterization
- Evasion technique selection based on WAF type
- Geographic and rule variation detection
- WAF mode identification (blocking vs monitoring)
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Send benign request to establish baseline response.
2. Send malicious payload to trigger WAF blocking.
3. Compare responses to detect WAF presence.
4. Analyze headers and cookies for vendor signatures.
5. Examine block page content for fingerprints.
6. Test multiple attack types to map rule coverage.
7. Probe rate limits and blocking thresholds.
8. Select appropriate bypass techniques based on findings.
</methodology>

